	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Anes wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">In, short, choosing a fixed time base is a dead end. The technique I use in nemulator is this:<br />- sync to 60Hz vblank<br />- generate your audio samples at freq f, and output to the directsound buffer<br />- query directsound for your buffer's playback and write cursor positions<br />- calculate distance between those positions<br />- choose a target distance, say 3000 bytes. This is the amount of data that you are trying to keep buffered<br />- every couple of frames, check how close you are to that target. Let's say you're at 3200 bytes. That means that you are generating too much audio data for your refresh rate. 2800 bytes? You're generating audio too slowly. Adjust your audio frequency, f, or playback frequency to compensate.</div><br /><br />I did it!! thxs for the info!!

		

		</td>
	</tr>
